In MSTest v4, `[ExpectedException]` was removed. The replacement is `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()` (or `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>()` for async methods). Here's how to migrate your tests:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}

[TestMethod]
public void Process_InvalidState_ThrowsInvalidOperation()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<InvalidOperationException>(() => Process());
}
```

**Key differences:**

| Old (v3) | New (v4) |
|----------|----------|
| `[ExpectedException(typeof(T))]` | `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>(() => ...)` |
| Matches derived types too | `ThrowsExactly` = exact type; use `Assert.Throws<T>` to include derived types |
| Attribute on method | Inline assertion — you can scope it to the exact line that should throw |

